<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-04-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-04-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="740" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d740">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/11749.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">W. H. Page</persName>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-28">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 28, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Sir Edward Grey informs me that under instructions from him Garden urged
                            Huerta to accept mediation proposed by South American Republics and
                            Garden has reported that Huerta assents. During Sir Edward’s absence in
                            Paris the Mexican Minister in London sent to the British Foreign Office
                            an unofficial request for British Government to offer mediation, which
                            Grey answered by saying that South American Republics had already done
                            so. But he spoke as if he would be willing to offer good offices of
                            British Government if need should arise.</p>
                        <p>I thanked Grey for helpful acts of Minister Carden and Admiral Cradock,
                            which seemed to please him.* * *</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>